I"§<p>Even though the milk kefir grains feeds on lactose resulting in a low-to-none lactose containing end product, milk kefir is not suitable for vegans. Thats why i want to train the milk kefir grains to ferment plant-based milk. Using plant-based milk is already possible, but because the plant-based milk doesnâ€™t contain any lactose the kefir grains will starve and eventually die.</p>

<p>I want to research if itâ€™s possible to slowly train the grains to eat other sources of sugar (forcing fast evolution). Iâ€™ll slowly introduce soy milk (because of its high protein).</p>

<p>Soy milk does contain sucrose and stachyose[^1] as the main sugar component. Because lactose breaks down into glucose and galactose (a sugar close to glucose) iâ€™ll add glucose to the soy-milk. I make the soy-milk myself, using 1L of water with 100g (dried) soybeans.</p>

<p>To see how the kefir grains improve when slowly transitioning i will have 2 control groups; 100% soy-milk, and 100% milk.</p>

<p>Each day iâ€™ll make a new batch, and examine the kefir grains based on their looks and reproduction/weight.</p>

